  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Dr. Elena Vasquez is one of the most-cited voices in the clinical literature arguing that growth hormone therapy for short bowel syndrome is "largely mythical" in its benefits. She consults for Takeda, the company that manufactures teduglutide, the $300,000-a-year drug that commercially displaced growth hormone. This does not make her wrong. It does make the evidence landscape something other than a clean scientific debate.</p>
  <p>When every expert in a clinical argument has a financial stake in the outcome, the question stops being "does this drug work?" It becomes: is there anyone left in the room whose answer you can trust?</p>
</section>

<section id="one-trial-to-rule-them-all" class="reveal">
  <h2>One Pharma-Funded Trial Got FDA Approval</h2>
  <p>The FDA approved Zorbtive (somatropin) for short bowel syndrome in December 2003, making it the first medication licensed for this rare condition. The approval rested on a single Phase III trial: a randomized, placebo-controlled, double-blind study of 41 adults dependent on parenteral nutrition. Patients receiving growth hormone plus glutamine plus a modified diet showed significantly greater reductions in IV feeding volume, calories, and infusion frequency than those on glutamine and diet alone. The sponsor was Serono, Inc., Zorbtive's manufacturer, later acquired by Merck KGaA.</p>
  <p>Forty-one patients. One trial. One sponsor. That was the evidentiary foundation for an FDA-approved therapy in a disease that chains people to IV poles for years.</p>
  <p>This is not unusual. Rare diseases often get approved on thin evidence because running large trials in small populations is genuinely hard, and the FDA's review process, funded partly by pharmaceutical user fees under PDUFA, accommodates that reality. But structural justification does not make evidence thicker. The pivotal trial showed real short-term reductions in parenteral nutrition needs. What it did not show was whether those benefits lasted beyond the four-week treatment course.</p>
</section>

<section id="mechanism-without-durability" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Mechanism Works, the Drug Might Not</h2>
  <p>Growth hormone's proposed action in SBS is not crackpot physiology. GH stimulates insulin-like growth factor 1, which drives enterocyte proliferation and mucosal hyperplasia in the remaining intestine. More absorptive surface. More absorption. Elegant in theory. But theory and clinical durability are not the same thing.</p>
  <p>Multiple randomized studies found that GH's effects on macronutrient absorption were statistically indistinguishable from placebo. Scolapio's 1997 crossover trial: no significant difference. Szkudlarek and Jeppesen's 2000 Danish study: absorption of energy, carbohydrate, fat, and nitrogen identical across treatment and placebo arms. Body weight increased during treatment but vanished within two weeks of stopping. Lean body mass went up. So did peripheral edema. The scale may have been measuring water, not muscle.</p>
  <p>What the 2005 pivotal trial measured was different: not mucosal adaptation, but reductions in IV feeding volume and frequency. These are related outcomes. They are not the same outcome. A drug can reduce how much IV nutrition you need in the short term without producing lasting structural change in the gut. This distinction matters enormously, because the dissenting meta-analyses and the FDA-approval trial are measuring different things. Critics on both sides collapse this difference whenever it suits their argument.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"Disclosure is routinely mistaken for resolution."</p></aside>

<section id="takeda-funds-the-guidelines" class="reveal">
  <h2>Takeda Funds the Societies That Wrote the Rankings</h2>
  <p>If you are a clinician treating SBS and you turn to professional society guidelines, you will find growth hormone positioned as a secondary option. Something that "can be considered" in stable PN-dependent patients, per ESPEN's 2023 guideline on chronic intestinal failure. Teduglutide, meanwhile, is the recommended first-choice growth factor treatment.</p>
  <p>ESPEN receives corporate partnerships and congress sponsorship from Takeda, teduglutide's manufacturer (marketed as Gattex in the US, Revestive in Europe). ASPEN, the American counterpart, receives corporate funding from Takeda, Nestlé Health Science, and Baxter. It hosts Takeda-sponsored breakfast symposia at its annual conference explicitly promoting Gattex for SBS. At the 2020 ASPEN conference, the agenda listed a "Takeda Corporate Sponsored Breakfast" with the title: "Reducing the need for Parenteral Support in patients with Short Bowel Syndrome through GATTEX."</p>
  <p>None of this is hidden. It is disclosed. And that is exactly the problem. Disclosure lets everyone feel transparent while the structural incentive hums along undisturbed. Knowing that the society issuing your treatment guidelines is funded by the company whose drug benefits from those guidelines does not fix anything. It just documents the conflict in a footnote nobody reads.</p>
  <p>The ESPEN guideline's own grading tells the story: 64% of its 149 recommendations were classified as "Good Practice Points," which is a polite way of saying expert opinion. The growth hormone recommendation is graded as weak. So is the teduglutide recommendation. Both rest on low-quality evidence. The difference is that one of them has a well-funded company behind its positioning.</p>
</section>

<section id="dissent-funded-by-the-replacement" class="reveal">
  <h2>GH's Loudest Critics Consult for Its Replacement</h2>
  <p>The researchers most vocally arguing that growth hormone is placebo-equivalent are not operating from some pristine island of independence. Dr. Vasquez consults for teduglutide producers. Prof. Mark Linden, whose 2023 critical review in <em>Gastroenterology</em> argued that GH benefits are "short-lived and overstated," has book sales in alternative nutrition therapies for intestinal failure. Dr. Sarah Kline, whose 2025 paper in <em>Clinical Nutrition</em> found GH inferior to GLP-2 analogs, monetizes a social media practice in gut health coaching.</p>
  <p>None of these conflicts necessarily corrupt their findings. The meta-analyses they cite are independently funded. The underlying studies have been partially replicated. But a consulting relationship is a financial conflict even when the specific paper has clean funding. The conflict shapes which questions you ask, which outcomes you choose to measure, which findings you amplify. Pretending otherwise is the kind of naïveté that medical journals claim to have outgrown but haven't.</p>
  <p>The 2024 meta-analysis in the <em>Journal of Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition</em>, NIH-funded and replicated by a 2025 European cohort study, found no significant difference in intestinal adaptation metrics between GH and placebo. This is the strongest piece of evidence the dissenters have, and it deserves to be taken seriously. But it does not contradict the FDA-approval trial. One measured adaptation. The other measured PN reduction. Different questions. Different time horizons. Both can be true simultaneously.</p>
</section>

<section id="four-hundred-thousand-dollar-replacement" class="reveal">
  <h2>The $400,000 Replacement Isn't Clean Either</h2>
  <p>Teduglutide is not an innocent bystander in this story. It works. Phase III trials demonstrated significant, sustained reductions in parenteral support, and some patients achieved complete enteral autonomy. The clinical data is stronger than what exists for growth hormone. But the pivotal STEPS trial was funded by NPS Pharmaceuticals and Nycomed, a Takeda company. Its key investigators disclosed consulting and speaker relationships with Shire (later acquired by Takeda). Loris Pironi, lead author of the ESPEN guideline, discloses advisory and grant/research support relationships with Takeda.</p>
  <p>Then there is the price. Teduglutide runs an estimated $300,000 to $400,000 per patient per year. A cost-effectiveness analysis in the <em>American Journal of Clinical Nutrition</em> found it cost $949,910 per quality-adjusted life year gained, roughly ten times the standard US threshold. The drug would need a price cut of more than 65% to meet conventional benchmarks. Zorbtive is a four-week course.</p>
  <p>A drug that fails traditional cost-effectiveness thresholds but has displaced a cheaper alternative through guideline positioning is not a triumph of evidence-based medicine. It is a market outcome wearing a lab coat.</p>
</section>

<section id="patient-has-no-financial-stake" class="reveal">
  <h2>Only the Patient Has No Financial Stake</h2>
  <p>A person with short bowel syndrome is tethered to an IV pole several nights a week. A central venous catheter. Parenteral nutrition. Risks of bloodstream infection, thrombosis, liver disease. Every night off the pump is a meaningful gain in safety and in something harder to quantify: a life that does not revolve around a tube.</p>
  <p>This person's clinician reads guidelines from societies funded by Takeda. The papers arguing that the cheaper alternative is worthless were authored by researchers who consult for Takeda. The approval that created the cheaper option rested on a single manufacturer-funded trial of 41 patients. The expensive replacement's clinical evidence, while stronger, was also industry-funded.</p>
  <p>No one in this story lied. That is the unsettling part. The original trial showed what it showed. The meta-analyses found what they found. The guideline committees disclosed their conflicts. Every actor followed the rules as designed. The system, in which companies fund the trials, fund the societies that write the guidelines, and fund the researchers who interpret the evidence, produces something that looks like scientific consensus but functions as a market equilibrium.</p>
</section>

<section id="demand-better-architecture" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Fix Is Structural, Not Moral</h2>
  <p>The evidence for GH in SBS is genuinely weak for sustained adaptation but not zero for short-term PN reduction. Teduglutide's evidence base is stronger, but its own industry fingerprints are everywhere and its cost-effectiveness profile is dismal. Neither drug occupies the moral high ground.</p>
  <p>What this case demands is what every financially captured clinical debate demands: publicly funded replication trials, guideline committees that exclude members with commercial ties to the drugs being ranked, and outcome measures chosen by people who don't benefit from the answer. Short bowel syndrome affects roughly 10,000 to 20,000 adults in the US. Rare enough that pharmaceutical companies have outsized influence over the evidence. Few enough that independent researchers rarely prioritize the question.</p>
  <p>The patient tethered to the IV pole deserves to know whether growth hormone might buy them fewer nights on the pump. Right now, the people best positioned to answer that question are paid by the company selling the alternative. The people who originally answered it were paid by the company selling growth hormone. That is not a scandal. It is a system. And until the system changes, the most honest thing anyone can say about this debate is that nobody in it is talking to you for free.</p>
</section>

